4. c3 { If white instead defends their d pawn, we have the same gameplan. Get the knight out, then the bishop, and then slide the pawn up. } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 { What do we do once the knight comes out? } 5... Bg4 6. Be2 { What's the next move in the setup? } 6... e6 7. O-O { Continue how you've been taught. } 7... Nge7 8. h3 { What do we do when the bishop gets attacked? } 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 { Take in the center. } 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 { Now our plan is going to involve targeting the weak d4 pawn. This can be with either the queen or the knight, as our knight on c6 already exerts a lot of pressure on the center of the board. The queen is typically better here, because we can also target the b2 pawn, overextending white's dark-squared bishop. } { [%csl Gd4,Gb6,Gf5][%cal Gc6d4,Gd8b6,Ge7f5] } *


