4. c4 { Here, white challenges our setup immediately with c4, known as the Panov, which resembles the Queen's Gambit. Here we are going to bring our knight out, and our light-squared bishop is going to stay at home for a bit. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 { Solidify the center with a pawn. } 5... e6 6. Nc3 { Get your bishop out to castle. } 6... Be7 7. Be2 { Since the bishop moved, we can now take the pawn, as white doesn't gain any development from capturing anymore. } 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 { Now castle! } 8... O-O 9. O-O { Next, we are going to push our b-pawn, to make a luft for our bishop. } 9... b6 { [%csl Gb7,Gc6][%cal Gc8b7,Gb8c6] } *


[Event "The Caro-Kann: The Classical Variation"]
[Date "2026.05.24"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Tartakower Variation"]
[StudyName "The Caro-Kann"]
[ChapterName "The Classical Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5b33uOBV/U5ulwaOa"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Booros"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2026.05.24"]
[UTCTime "22:38:27"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

3. Nc3 { If White plays their queenside knight out to either square defending their pawn, we are going to take the pawn. This is known as the Tarktakower. } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { After they recapture, we are going to attack the knight with our knight. } 4... Nf6 { If our opponent doesn't take here, we are going to just develop normally, bringing out our bishop and knight (Green), before using an e- or c-pawn break to open the position (Blue), maybe playing e6 to get our bishop out and castle kingside (Yellow). } { [%csl Bc5,Be5,Gf5,Gd7,Ye6,Ye7,Yg8,Yf8][%cal Be7e5,Bc6c5,Gb8d7,Gc8f5,Ye7e6,Yf8e7,Ye8g8,Yh8f8] } (4... Nd7 { This is known as the Karpov variation, and the goal is to bring the knight out with a delay, so we don't double our pawns and still get a knight on f6. } 5. c3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6) (4... Bf5 { This is also a proper move, attacking the knight immediately. This move order is just more highly theoretical, and so we avoid it in this study. } 5. Ng3 Bg6) 5. Nxf6+ { If white takes, however, we are going to take with the e-pawn. } 5... exf6 6. Bd3 { Get the bishop out next. } 6... Bd6 7. Nf3 { Now castle. } 7... O-O 8. O-O { Slide the rook to the open file. } 8... Re8 { The gameplan here is to move your knight out, then your bishop up, and then the queen, connecting your rooks. Here is one continuation that you might get in your games, leading to a quick win. } { [%csl Rd7,Be6,Gg6][%cal Gb8d7,Rd8d7,Bc8e6,Gd7f8,Gf8g6] } 9. Be3 { Follow the gameplan. } 9... Nd7 10. Qd2 { Follow the gameplan. } 10... Nf8 11. c3 { Follow the gameplan. } 11... Be6 12. Rfe1 { Follow the gameplan. } 12... Qd7 13. h3 { Here white plays a very lazy move, h3. Now we get a very nice trick in these positions. We can actually sacrifice our bishop on h3! } 13... Bxh3 14. gxh3 { Bring in the queen! } 14... Qxh3 { [%csl Gh2,Rf3][%cal Gh3h2,Gd6h2,Rh3f3] } 15. Be2 { White backs the bishop up to defend the knight. Here we bring our rook up and over. } 15... Re4 { Here we have a large threat on the king. White has no escape squares, and rook to g4 is mate. The position from here is a win with proper play. } { [%csl Rh1,Rh2,Rg2,Rf1,Bg4,Bg1][%cal Be4g4,Bg4g1,Rh3f1,Rh3h1] } *


