3. f3 { If we see f3, this is the start of the Fantasy variation. Here, we are not going to take, as that is exactly what white wants us to do. Instead, we are going to go for a fianchetto setup, almost like a Dragon Sicilian, Kings Indian, or Grünfeld, but with slightly different pawn structure on the queenside. } 3... g6 4. Nc3 { Here we fianchetto the bishop. } 4... Bg7 5. Be3 { If we see the bishop come out early, we are going to slide our queen to b6, targeting the pawn the bishop left undefended. } 5... Qb6 6. Qd2 { This is a tricky line, where white wants to target our queen with their rook after we take, but we actually have an escape square still, and so we are fine. } 6... Qxb2 7. Rb1 { Go to the escape square. } 7... Qa3 8. exd5 { If white takes the pawn here, we are going to develop our knight out. } 8... Nf6 *


